  "prompt": "Why when I urinate does my urine sometimes come out in two directions simultaneously?",
  "response": "Having your urine stream split in two directions is most often caused by a temporary and usually harmless issue with your urethra, the tube that carries urine from your bladder out of your body. Here's a breakdown of the most common reasons:\n\n*   **Mild Swelling or Irritation of the Urethral Opening (Meatus):** This is the most frequent cause. Even slight irritation or minor swelling at the tip of the urethra can disrupt the flow and cause it to split. This irritation can be caused by:\n    *   **Vigorous or frequent sexual activity:** This can cause minor trauma or inflammation.\n    *   **Soap or other irritants:** Certain soaps, lotions, or detergents can irritate the sensitive skin around the urethra.\n    *   **Chafing:** Tight clothing or exercise can cause friction and irritation.\n    *   **Minor UTIs (Urinary Tract Infections):** UTIs can inflame the urethra.\n    *   **Dehydration:** Concentrated urine can be more irritating.\n\n*   **Temporary Obstruction or Adhesion:** A tiny piece of dried urine, a small flake of skin, or even a stray hair can temporarily block part of the urethral opening, leading to a split stream.\n\n*   **Urethral Stricture:** This is a narrowing of the urethra. While it can cause a split stream, it's often accompanied by other symptoms like difficulty urinating, weak stream, dribbling, or pain during urination. This is more common in men than women. Urethral strictures can be caused by inflammation, infection, injury, or scar tissue from prior surgery.\n\n*   **Meatitis:** This is inflammation of the urethral opening. This is more common in circumcised men.\n\n*   **Prostate Issues (in men):** An enlarged prostate (benign prostatic hyperplasia or BPH) can put pressure on the urethra and distort the flow.\n\n**When to Worry and Seek Medical Advice:**\n\nWhile a split stream is often harmless, you should see a doctor if you experience any of the following along with it:\n\n*   **Pain or burning during urination**\n*   **Frequent urination**\n*   **Urgent need to urinate**\n*   **Difficulty starting or stopping urination**\n*   **Weak urine stream**\n*   **Dribbling after urination**\n*   **Blood in the urine**\n*   **Pelvic pain**\n*   **Discharge from the penis (in men)**\n\nThese symptoms could indicate a more serious underlying problem like a UTI, urethral stricture, or prostate issue.\n\n**What You Can Do:**\n\n*   **Stay hydrated:** Drink plenty of water to keep your urine dilute and less irritating.\n*   **Practice good hygiene:** Gently wash the area around your urethra with mild soap and water. Avoid harsh soaps or scented products.\n*   **Avoid irritants:** Identify and avoid any soaps, lotions, or clothing that seem to irritate the area.\n*   **Empty your bladder completely:** Try to relax and take your time when urinating.\n*   **If you suspect a UTI, see a doctor:** They can test your urine and prescribe antibiotics if needed.\n\n**In summary, a split urine stream is often a temporary and benign issue. However, if it's persistent or accompanied by other symptoms, it's best to consult a doctor to rule out any underlying medical conditions.**\n",
